title: LCLS User Meeting Notes:
text:
Executive summary: pretty vanilla week! Yay!

MFX LY64 Kern (Thu-Sun day shift):

Structural dynamics of metalloenzymes that catalyze reactions of small molecules relevant for the energy economy.

Studying mainly Methane monooxygenase (converts methane into methanol to reduce methane emissions), also studying RNR R2a, Hydrogenase, Nitrogenase and MCR.

Time resolved RT X-ray measurements.

  • Multiplexing with XPP
  • 9.8 keV photons (10.7 GeV electrons)
  • Will be using pulse picker (can only run at 30 or 20 Hz)
  • Maximum pulse energy
  • Pulse duration optimized for maximum pulse energy

XPP LX88 Savoini (Thu-Mon day shift):

Multidimensional pathways for coherent control of ferroic order via soft phonon modes

Understand/design a new way of controlling ferroelectric material (material with a spontaneous electrical polarization that can be switched by an applied E-field). Used as memory, advantage of low-current switching.

Hard x-ray diffraction from regular Bragg peaks.

  • Multiplexing with MFX
  • 9.8 keV photons (10.7 GeV electrons), using a monochromator
  • Pulse energy not critical, need > 0.5 mJ before mono. Higher than that not a problem
  • Pulse duration 50 fs or shorter
  • Narrow bandwidth for spectral brightness
  • Stability in space (pointing), energy and time are all important

XCS LY54 Hadt (Thu-Sun night shift):

Structural and Dynamic Basis for Quantum Effects in Enzyme Catalysis

Study Cytochrome P450cam, an important enzyme for human life (we all have it in our liver!).

Using XAS to unravel the roles of ultrafast couplings between atomic motions and electronic structure after photoexcitation

  • Vanilla 8 keV photons (9.65 GeV electrons)
  • Nominal pulse duration
  • Maximum pulse energy

MFX P217/P218 Schofield/Rabe (Mon day shift):

Studying various enzymes (IPNS, AlkB, etc).

  • 9.8 keV photons (10.7 GeV electrons)
  • Maximum pulse energy
  • Pulse duration optimized for max pulse energy

text: 3/9/22 Q2E Troubleshoot/Find â CATER 155476 1. In order to safely test/investigate Q2E magnet, we LOTO the next to magnets as follows: a.
